"Yes, chief. They must be on their way, now, we gave them time to get supplies from the mess." At 5:00 AM sharp, the Exodus company was assembled at the vehicle park. Shaw climbed onto a crate and began to speak.
"We're deploying to FOB I-131, eighty kilometers from Ianlos. We have to support the ongoing siege and the planned attack on Ianlos to quell the insurgency. From there, we'll have an advanced position and a base at the foot of the mountains," explained Shaw. "Gather your units, and board."
The company dispersed, with each member joining their unit, and the sergeants made them board the tanks. Cohren climbed aboard one of the armoured vehicles, at the front of the convoy, and joined Nemic, Craith, and two new recruits. Cohren remembered their arrival a few days earlier, but he didn't know much about them. Sitting on the side, his legs dangling, he adjusted his backpack and his radio equipment, which was connected to his earpiece and throat mic.
"Hey Cohren, has Harris still got Snowball?", asked Nemic as they settled in.
"You mean the chicken he stole?", Cohren remembered the morning they had stolen it from a farm. "Yes, I'm sure of it".
Cohren cast an eye towards one of the armor and spotted Harris with his unit. From behind his pack, he could just make out the movement of a small chicken bobbing its head to observe the surroundings.
"Yeah, he's got it", Cohren replied as the turret of the armor creaked open to let his commander pass through.
"All the tanks are moving", declared calmly, but clearly the commander in his helmet. The engines of a platoon of tanks and Strykers roared as they began to advance. The Kronos on which Cohren was located jerked when its brakes were released and it started moving to fall into formation. The tanks deployed in a V to cross the plains of Itania. The winter storms had frozen the marshes and forests, but the mud was still there.
About an hour later, one of the new recruits, named Orson in Cohren's memory, spoke up. "Lieutenant, you've been here since the start of the war, haven't you?"
"Yeah, Operation Tempest Fire", Cohren replied. "We thought we'd wrap it up in a few weeks, but... we underestimated them."
"Underestimating is a weak word," Nemic said, joining in on the conversation. "They had more arms and men than we had anticipated. They managed to take down the UFS Revenant in the first two weeks, and Erebus last month. Shit, we should have seen it from the road where we are."
"Well, I'll hold out for the Federation," Orson said with a bit of provocation. "I won't let these terrorists scare me."
"You're saying that now, but from experience, I know that the new young recruits like you who are 18 years old take cover the moment they hear a shot," Craith declared.
"I think we'll soon be sorted out," said Corhen, laughing. Orson didn't follow up on the conversation.
"Exodus XO, Exodus CO," Cohren's radio crackled. "We're detecting thermal signatures about 300 meters away, 20 degrees to the right."
Cohren stood up on top of the vehicle and put on his optical glasses. By activating thermal vision, he could see thermal signatures far away.
"Yeah, I see them", Cohren replied via his throat microphone.
"Enemies?", asked the other recruit, Natayla.
"Impossible to say", declared Cohren. He activated his microphone and said: "Exodus Company, do not fire unless you are fired upon, let them out."
As they got closer, the small thermal signatures passed from blurry spots to more distinct shapes. As they got even closer, one of them ran towards something, grabbed it, then rushed back to the small ridge where they were. The silhouettes got into firing position.
"We've got contacts," Shaw cried out over the radio, as orange tracers were fired from the ridge. The bullets ricocheted off the sides of the tanks, as the soldiers leaped from the vehicles to take cover behind them. A tank-killing missile whizzed by and slammed into the ground behind the formation, exploding and sending debris flying onto one of the vehicles. Another missile hit the side of a Stryker, an APS-Cerberus, and exploded. Its crew extricated themselves and dove for cover as the ammunition ignited.
"Iron 1-2 and &-", 25 degrees right, 275 meters." 'Fire,' the tank platoon commander yelled over the radio. Iron 1-2 and 1-3 opened fire, their shells flew towards the ridge and exploded, sending mud and rocks into the air.
"Send in the Senti," Knoxx cried out, observing the ridge through his binoculars. The rear of one of the Cerberus opened and an unarmed soldier with a special helmet stepped out. He bellowed orders into a square microphone, and two Senti, or Sentinelles as they were officially known, rushed out. Their thin metal arms and legs swung forward as they sprinted into action. They were armed, but their arms were attached to their backs.
"Do we take them out or capture them?" Craith asked, as they watched.
"It seems we're capturing them," Cohren said, as the two Sentinelles disappeared into a cloud of smoke and ash. Cries and gunfire echoed from the ridge, but ceased quickly. A moment later, the two Sentinelles returned, dragging someone behind them, whose boots trailed on the ground. Once safely with the platoon, they threw the individual to the ground. He groaned in pain as he collapsed into the mud and snow.
Shaw walked towards the individual, who was starting to get up. He turned towards one of the Sentinels. "How many?"
"Three dead, chief," replied the Sentinel. "The others fled on foot."
Shaw nodded his head and turned towards Cohren and Craith, who were standing beside him. "Both of you, would you have the kindness to get rid of this man?"
